<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06096146 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06096146 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  OAKLAND; BASEBALL; CLUB; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  It was just a tuneup for Dave Stewart, and those were University of Californiakids standing at the plate. But hey, there was professional pride at stakeThursday afternoon at the Coliseum.;    &quot;That was like pitching against myson,&quot; said Stewart after polishing off the Bears with seven shutout innings ofthree-hit work. Stewart struck out six and didn't issue a walk.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  STEWART SHOWS CAL KIDS THE ROPESA'S ACE SHUTS OUT BEARS ON THREE HITS OVERSEVEN INNINGS  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  BaseballA'sNotebook  </MEMO><TEXT>     Although Stewart said &quot;I needed to get some work in, so I went out thereand worked on things I needed this season,&quot; it looked as if he was pumping upthe volume on his fastball in the later innings.;    He acknowledged he wantedto show the kids a little something.;    &quot;It's just to let 'em know. Earlierthey thought they were doing something. Later on, I wanted them to know, heck,I don't know you like you don't me. But let me have one time through thelineup and I'll show you what it's about,&quot; he said.;    Stewart gave up adouble to third baseman Dan Cholowsky when he threw him three straightforkballs, followed by a fastball. And he discounted the double because thecollege players were using aluminum bats.;    Asked to envision what teammateJose Canseco would do with an aluminum bat, Stewart said. &quot;That would be acrime.&quot;;    Rookie Dana Allison worked the eighth and final inning in the A's4-0 win, giving up a hit.;    A's Manager Tony La Russa said the A's got &quot;justabout exactly&quot; what they needed out of the game.; INJURY REPORT: First basemanMark McGwire, who had a cortisone shot in his back Wednesday, is expected toplay tonight. McGwire worked out Thursday. . . . Left fielder Rickey Hendersonwas still troubled by tendinitis in his left shoulder. He didn't see a doctor,but trainer Barry Weinberg said he'll be examined today.; ETC.: Catcher EddieTaubensee, one of the A's two Rule-5 draft picks off the Cincinnati Reds'minor league roster, was claimed on waivers by the Cleveland Indians. A teammust keep a Rule-5 pick on its major league roster or offer him back to hisoriginal team. Before, players had to clear waivers to return to their firstteam. A's General Manager Sandy Alderson said pitcher Joe Turek's situationremains unresolved. . . . Stewart, Jim Abbott, Alvin Davis, Mark Langston andDanny Jackson led off baseball's campaign urging students to do well inschool. They taped public-service messages to be aired this summer ontelevision and radio in cooperation with the National Education Association.Print messages also will be used.;  BAY BRIDGE SERIES AT A GLANCE; GIANTS VS.A'S; Game times and sites: Today -- Giants vs. A's, 7:35 p.m., at theColiseum. Saturday -- Giants vs. A's, 1:05 p.m., at the Coliseum. Sunday --Giants vs. the A's, 1:05 p.m., at Candlestick Park.; Television: Today --CH36, 7:30 p.m. Saturday -- SportsChannel, 1 p.m.; Radio: All three games willbe on KNBR (680), KSFO (560), KLOK (1170) and KNTA (1430).; Pitching matchups:Today -- The Giants' Bud Black vs. Bob Welch. Saturday -- Rick Reuschel orScott Garrelts vs. Eric Show. Sunday -- Mike LaCoss vs. Mike Moore.; Ticketinformation: Plenty of tickets are available for all three games.; Traveler'stip: Tonight, keep in mind the Warriors are playing at the Coliseum Arena, andboth games start at about the same time. So traffic will be heavy. Warriorsofficials suggest fans take BART to either the basketball or baseball game.;-- Mercury News Staff  </TEXT><BYLINE>  KIM BOATMAN, Mercury News Staff Writer  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Oakland  </CITY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910405  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Friday  </DAY><MONTH>  April  </MONTH><PG.CO